WEBVTT

00:00.578 --> 00:04.904
In the Bay Area, we are obsessed with arrival.

00:04.944 --> 00:05.745
Have you noticed that?

00:06.065 --> 00:12.154
Even the ways that we get places, it will tell us the time that we plan on arriving.

00:12.174 --> 00:17.000
We live our lives in a constant state of future tense.

00:17.721 --> 00:21.426
We are all tempted to tell the story of our lives

00:21.666 --> 00:24.609
kind of this way in our minds, whether we realize it or not.

00:24.710 --> 00:30.476
When I get the IPO, when we get acquired, then I'll finally be able to rest.

00:31.117 --> 00:36.904
When I get that house in that neighborhood, then I'll finally choose to invest in real community.

00:36.924 --> 00:40.048
When I get married or when we have kids, then we'll be happy.

00:40.068 --> 00:43.251
For some of you, it's like when my kids move out, I'll finally be happy.

00:43.912 --> 00:45.394
We treat wherever

00:45.474 --> 00:51.740
We are right now, whatever moment we're in today, like it's the waiting room of where we hope will eventually be.

00:52.501 --> 00:58.366
We ultimately treat our actual lives like we are commuting to the life we really dream of.

00:59.327 --> 01:14.962
It's kind of our 21st century version of the Promised Land because we believe it's the life we deserve and secretly we wonder if the reason that we feel so alone or isolated from God is because God is waiting for us at the finish line of our self-constructed Promised Land.

01:15.618 --> 01:19.403
And that works in Silicon Valley until it doesn't.

01:20.564 --> 01:33.740
When the map breaks, when you lose the job, when the relationship fizzles, when depression returns, you can realize that maybe it feels like you're no closer than you were to the promised land of your own creation.

01:33.760 --> 01:36.684
As a matter of fact, maybe it feels like you're further than you ever were.

01:36.724 --> 01:39.287
You're actually in the desert of your life.

01:39.347 --> 01:45.234
And honestly, those are moments when we start to sound a lot like kids on a long road trip.

01:45.634 --> 01:47.797
If you have kids, you've heard this before.

01:47.857 --> 01:49.940
If you've been around kids, you've probably heard this before.

01:50.000 --> 02:00.214
But any trip, any experience of any distance, you will have kids in the back of the car that just sort of like with a little bit of a nasally annoyed sound go, are we there yet?

02:00.254 --> 02:02.817
You know, which I just want to spotlight this for you.

02:02.878 --> 02:06.522
If you're a kid that does this, I want you to understand what it used to be.

02:06.943 --> 02:10.067
My parents used something called a map.

02:10.508 --> 02:14.994
And that map, it was on something called paper.

02:15.138 --> 02:18.222
And we didn't know when we were going to arrive somewhere.

02:18.282 --> 02:23.330
But when my kids ask this question, I'm like, there's a giant screen that you can see.

02:23.370 --> 02:27.295
And it actually tells you when we're going to get there.

02:27.796 --> 02:30.339
And then if it's a long trip, you also have a screen.

02:30.359 --> 02:34.585
Anyway, just a totally, that's just me venting for a minute, right?

02:35.427 --> 02:38.030
And it's easy in a moment like that to like kind of joke around.

02:38.070 --> 02:39.292
We understand the concept of time.

02:39.312 --> 02:39.913
We know distance.

02:39.933 --> 02:40.954
We know how long it's going to take.

02:41.355 --> 02:43.538
And we just think that's cute that our kids do that.

02:44.322 --> 02:48.448
But I wonder how many of us kind of sound a little bit like that with God.

02:49.310 --> 02:52.154
And we're asking, like God, am I there yet?

02:53.136 --> 03:04.754
God, am I to the part of my life that my life will finally make sense, where anxiety will finally subside, where I finally feel like I'm enough, like I've arrived.

03:05.474 --> 03:17.429
See, we spend our whole lives leaning forward, trying to get a head start, get around this lower car, choose the right lane, straining to see the destination convinced that God is waiting for us across the finish line.

03:17.949 --> 03:18.971
But what if he isn't?

03:19.912 --> 03:27.281
What if the most disorienting fact about the wilderness reality of our lives is that God is actually waiting for us in the desert, not at the destination?

03:28.022 --> 03:34.610
That the thing you think, I'll finally spend time with God when I get to where he is and he's been with you the whole time.

03:35.330 --> 03:40.638
Today, across all of our campuses, we are starting a journey called Lent toward Easter.

03:40.658 --> 03:43.402
It's the period of anticipation, of preparation.

03:43.443 --> 03:58.706
It's a series we're calling, I Am, where we're going to look at these stories, these little vignettes through the Hebrew Scriptures, what we often call the Old Testament, where God gets close to people in painful and difficult situations as a reminder that that's actually what God still wants to do.

03:58.946 --> 04:07.621
Today, it's about a God who he doesn't wait for you to get out of a mess to introduce yourself to him or intervene in areas maybe for you that feel overwhelming.

04:07.661 --> 04:09.424
He wants you to walk with him in them.

04:10.185 --> 04:15.154
We're going to look at Exodus 3 where a man named Moses shows us what this looks like.

04:15.618 --> 04:18.845
His dream of the promised land had died decades earlier.

04:18.946 --> 04:29.149
He had given up on that kind of life and he was stuck in the middle of nowhere, assuming the best days of his life and the best future that he could have imagined had already passed him by.

04:29.189 --> 04:33.138
And that's exactly the moment that God chose to stop by.

04:33.762 --> 04:42.310
But before we dive into the text, I'm just gonna invite you, no matter what you are walking in with today, some of you, you're here today and you have other work to do today.

04:42.630 --> 04:54.862
Some of you are thinking about the week ahead of you or what's behind you and this idea of constantly living in anticipation of it, a future arrival, I would just say take a moment and stop the car, stop the commute, stop the race.

04:56.884 --> 04:59.687
And let's just, maybe let's stop asking for a minute, are we there yet?

05:00.468 --> 05:03.090
And thank God that he's here with us right now.

05:03.522 --> 05:04.243
Would you pray with me?

05:05.925 --> 05:13.015
God, we all come into a space like this, and Mountain View, and Saratoga, and San Mateo, and Menlo Park, online around the world.

05:13.095 --> 05:15.439
And God, we have different needs.

05:15.459 --> 05:16.500
We have different expectations.

05:16.520 --> 05:17.261
We have different hopes.

05:17.702 --> 05:20.125
And wherever we are, God, you are already there.

05:21.427 --> 05:32.242
And so would you help us to relate to you, not as some far off, distant, disinterested being, but as someone who has come near, who is just as present today as you have ever been.

05:33.058 --> 05:35.021
Help us to experience that in a new way today.

05:36.123 --> 05:37.925
In Jesus' name.

05:37.945 --> 05:38.126
Amen.

05:39.608 --> 05:49.543
Now, before we open the text together, I know that when I say Moses, there's kind of a range of potential mental images that come to your mind.

05:49.903 --> 05:53.028
Some of it is based on your upbringing, some of it is based on your age.

05:53.509 --> 05:59.538
If you didn't grow up in church, or maybe you only received your mosaic history lesson from the Prince of Egypt, right?

05:59.970 --> 06:05.278
Let me give you a quick refresher on Moses' life so that we're all coming to it at the same place.

06:05.779 --> 06:09.344
Moses' life, think about it like three 40-year chapters.

06:09.425 --> 06:10.887
He lived a long life.

06:11.308 --> 06:18.098
In the first section of his life, Moses is born as a Hebrew slave under a death sentence from a tyrannical king.

06:18.690 --> 06:22.961
As a matter of fact, his mom puts him in a basket and floats him down the river.

06:22.981 --> 06:30.521
And while this sounds like child endangerment, what was really happening was trying to make the best option available in a very impossible situation.

06:30.942 --> 06:35.314
And he's found by Pharaoh's daughter and ultimately adopted into the royal

06:35.362 --> 06:35.803
family.

06:35.823 --> 06:40.109
So this young man ends up growing up with the best education, the best food, the best life.

06:40.149 --> 06:42.772
Think like tech billionaire's child era, right?

06:42.793 --> 06:44.295
That's what he's in the midst of.

06:44.655 --> 06:46.358
He's super heavily invested.

06:46.398 --> 06:47.439
He has power.

06:47.479 --> 06:48.180
He has status.

06:48.220 --> 06:49.001
He has influence.

06:49.302 --> 07:00.818
But around age 40, after decades of watching people who look like him face abuse, his own people, actually there's some scholars that believe he's trying to start an uprising and all of this sort of

07:01.570 --> 07:02.491
Bubbles up.

07:02.511 --> 07:15.010
One day, he sees an Egyptian guard beating a Hebrew slave, and after years of disengagement, with rage that had been brewing under the surface, he snaps, he kills the Egyptian, and he hides that person's body in the sand.

07:15.752 --> 07:18.155
It didn't bring about the uprising that maybe he'd hoped.

07:18.636 --> 07:22.121
As a matter of fact, a hit gets put out on him, and everybody turns on him.

07:22.782 --> 07:25.266
Overnight, he goes from prince to pariah.

07:26.050 --> 07:34.261
And as a result, he runs for his life into the desert to a place called Midian, which is kind of like moving to the middle of nowhere in a camper van with a flat tire.

07:34.621 --> 07:37.645
His life was not headed in a great direction.

07:38.266 --> 07:39.828
And that's where the story starts today.

07:40.429 --> 07:44.654
But Moses has been there in the desert for 40 years.

07:45.115 --> 07:48.739
Let that sink in for just a minute, like 40 more years.

07:48.779 --> 07:51.283
He isn't a young revolutionary anymore.

07:51.643 --> 07:53.906
He's an 80-year-old shepherd.

07:54.306 --> 08:00.736
He went from ruling an empire to wiping sheep noses and probably more than just their noses for decades.

08:01.698 --> 08:04.843
He went from the palace to working for his father-in-law.

08:04.923 --> 08:07.327
Talk about a humbling slide.

08:08.309 --> 08:09.931
He's not looking for God anymore.

08:10.693 --> 08:12.235
He's not looking for purpose anymore.

08:13.057 --> 08:14.279
He's looking for a lost sheep.

08:15.220 --> 08:18.866
His linked in profile had long since been deleted for inactivity.

08:19.458 --> 08:23.364
His dreams are buried with that Egyptian back in the sand.

08:23.404 --> 08:27.611
He has assumed for decades that his story is over.

08:28.512 --> 08:36.685
But as he rounds the corner on his daily rounds in the mountain called Oreb, he sees a bush that is on fire but not burning up.

08:36.745 --> 08:41.553
And this little glitch in the matrix of the moment, and you're like, are you referencing the matrix?

08:41.573 --> 08:42.895
I sure am, I'm a millennial.

08:43.596 --> 08:44.658
This little glitch

08:44.834 --> 08:51.682
In the matrix of the desert, all those years ago would change everything for Moses and for God's people.

08:52.383 --> 08:56.187
So let's look at the first few verses of Exodus three together.

08:56.207 --> 08:56.828
It reads this way.

08:57.128 --> 09:01.533
Now Moses was keeping the flock of his father-in-law, Jethro, the priest of Midian.

09:02.134 --> 09:06.659
And he led his flock to the west side of the wilderness and came to Oreb, the mountain of God.

09:07.300 --> 09:12.466
And the angel of the Lord appeared to him in a flame of fire out of the midst of a bush.

09:12.994 --> 09:16.078
He looked, and behold, the bush was burning, yet it was not consumed.

09:16.118 --> 09:21.684
And Moses said, I will turn aside to see this great sight, why the bush is not burned.

09:22.265 --> 09:26.610
When the Lord saw he turned aside to see, God called him out of the bush, Moses.

09:28.232 --> 09:29.653
Moses.

09:29.673 --> 09:33.778
Now this is like a wild moment, but it's wild because of how ordinary it is.

09:34.419 --> 09:37.042
This was just a random work day for Moses.

09:37.442 --> 09:45.734
And while Hollywood may have added some other things to it and whatever version you've seen, or if we could do this now, we'd probably add a bunch of CGI onto whatever was happening.

09:46.094 --> 09:50.560
For Moses, this was just a bush in a desert full of bushes.

09:51.482 --> 09:55.908
Scholars believe that this was likely an acacia bush, a desert weed.

09:55.968 --> 09:57.650
This was not unique.

09:57.751 --> 10:00.975
And actually, it wouldn't have been that unique to see it on fire.

10:01.276 --> 10:05.842
You're in the middle of a desert, and it was a dry plant in extreme heat.

10:06.690 --> 10:12.956
What made it unique, what made it different was that this bush kept burning.

10:12.976 --> 10:15.498
It didn't burn up, it didn't drop ash.

10:16.720 --> 10:18.501
But note the detail in verse three.

10:19.502 --> 10:24.207
Moses, he decides to stop and observe this unique moment on an ordinary day.

10:24.847 --> 10:30.713
That moment, that pause is what God used as the moment to call him closer.

10:31.374 --> 10:35.858
God didn't speak until Moses stopped, until Moses listened.

10:36.738 --> 10:42.466
In a moment like this, we can catch the fire very easily when we read this passage, but we miss the moment if we're not careful.

10:42.546 --> 10:44.108
The voice of God was not absent.

10:44.509 --> 10:46.031
It was waiting for attention.

10:46.111 --> 10:47.453
We should pay attention to that.

10:48.394 --> 10:51.739
Sometimes people ask me why we don't hear God more regularly in 2026.

10:52.299 --> 10:58.448
And I think there are a lot of good answers to that question, but it's certainly not because God has less to say in 2026.

10:58.628 --> 11:05.938
I think at least part of the answer is we have less time, less attention and less interest to listen.

11:07.106 --> 11:14.096
If we were to transport this moment to the typical Bay Area Moses, his headphones are in.

11:15.257 --> 11:19.163
He's listening to a podcast on how to optimize sheep herding at 2x speed.

11:20.404 --> 11:24.070
He's consulting AI, which back then was ancient intelligence, very different thing.

11:25.752 --> 11:28.356
He was doing an all on a stone tablet, amazing battery life.

11:29.297 --> 11:31.460
And he'd walk right by this bush, wouldn't he?

11:32.001 --> 11:33.042
He'd be like, what fire?

11:33.378 --> 11:38.866
He might see something in the distance, but in the midst of everything that he was trying to get done in that day, he might have thought, you know what, somebody else will take care of that.

11:38.886 --> 11:40.908
That's not my problem.

11:42.290 --> 11:45.495
But in this moment, Moses turns and he looks.

11:46.716 --> 11:48.739
He deviates from his deadlines.

11:49.080 --> 11:52.725
He allows his curiosity for God to override his productivity in the moment.

11:53.306 --> 11:54.247
When's the last time you did that?

11:55.348 --> 11:56.710
Here's a question for you.

11:56.730 --> 12:02.258
How many burning bush moments have you missed this week on your way to your own self-constructed promised land?

12:03.970 --> 12:16.884
How many times has God stopped and tapped you on the shoulder in a conversation with your spouse, a moment with your colleagues, your kids, your classmates, your neighbors, and you just optimized it away in your mind even in the midst of it.

12:16.904 --> 12:18.766
You were already thinking, how can I be done with this?

12:20.128 --> 12:23.371
What if your efficiency has squeezed out encounters with God in your life?

12:24.513 --> 12:28.116
Not in the distant past, not decades ago, days ago.

12:28.997 --> 12:33.202
See over and over and over again in the Bible, God describes himself as,

12:33.410 --> 12:41.362
I am, the always ready, always existing creator and sustainer of the universe.

12:42.684 --> 12:49.033
The problem is we have trouble seeing the signs of I am with a life that we are so addicted to I do.

12:50.055 --> 12:54.962
When Moses makes time for it, he has an encounter that changes his entire life.

12:55.623 --> 12:56.825
Verse five continues this way.

12:56.845 --> 12:59.509
It says, then he said, do not come near.

13:00.110 --> 13:02.834
Take your sandals off your feet for the place

13:03.650 --> 13:06.935
on which you are standing is holy ground.

13:07.976 --> 13:10.960
Now Moses had likely been to this specific place that he's in before.

13:11.020 --> 13:13.744
Nothing about the dirt around him felt particularly holy.

13:14.024 --> 13:18.390
The thing that made this place holy today is God's unique presence in it.

13:19.252 --> 13:24.259
And it shows the necessity of the desert for Moses and for you and me.

13:24.719 --> 13:28.144
Part of that is because the desert dismantles what deforms us.

13:28.625 --> 13:32.530
The thing we didn't see coming, the thing that we have let attach itself to us

13:32.770 --> 13:34.333
The desert clarifies all of it.

13:34.914 --> 13:38.500
When God tells Moses to take off his sandals, it wasn't about hygiene.

13:39.182 --> 13:41.906
In the ancient world, sandals were about protection.

13:42.427 --> 13:46.354
They were a layer that separated you from the heat, from the thorns, from the filth.

13:46.395 --> 13:48.458
They insulated you from your surroundings.

13:49.200 --> 13:54.229
And God is saying to Moses that if we're going to do this, you're going to have to feel what's real.

13:54.249 --> 13:57.234
You're going to have to look at yourself clearly in the mirror.

13:57.794 --> 13:59.476
and face the facts of the moment.

13:59.496 --> 14:07.225
Now, Moses had already had layers of himself removed over the course of decades, which tells you something about the more that needed to be pulled back.

14:07.726 --> 14:09.908
He had lost his status as a prince.

14:10.329 --> 14:12.551
He had lost his power in the Pharaoh's court.

14:12.852 --> 14:15.134
He had lost his platform as a revolutionary.

14:15.395 --> 14:17.417
He had lost control over his destiny.

14:17.497 --> 14:20.360
And now God is asking for his shoes.

14:22.162 --> 14:25.266
See, the desert, it dismantles your false identity.

14:25.538 --> 14:28.442
as you can finally meet God on his terms.

14:29.123 --> 14:37.676
Whatever level of self-construed control, whatever self-protection stuff we put up, God will just use the desert to pull it back.

14:38.417 --> 14:44.306
See, it's hard to come before the great I am when in the back of your mind you're thinking, does he know how great I am?

14:45.666 --> 14:48.190
The desert, it just clears that clutter instantly.

14:48.230 --> 14:53.278
It removes who you thought you were, and it shows you who you really are.

14:53.298 --> 14:58.646
More importantly, it shows you who God really is, and then who you are gets shaped out of that.

14:59.628 --> 15:04.015
The second thing that the desert does is it reveals God's heart for you and me.

15:04.676 --> 15:11.346
In the first few verses, it shows us what the desert takes, but the second section shows us what the desert gives back.

15:11.650 --> 15:16.716
verses seven and eight give this beautiful description of God's care for his people in the Old Testament.

15:16.736 --> 15:26.047
It says this in the Lord said, I have surely seen the affliction of my people who are in Egypt and have heard their cry because of their taskmasters.

15:26.207 --> 15:38.642
I know their sufferings and I have come down to deliver them out of the hand of the Egyptians and to bring them up out of that land to a good and broad land, a land flowing with milk and honey.

15:38.946 --> 15:44.572
to the place of the Canaanites, the Hittites, the Emmerites, the Prizites, the Hivites, and the Jebusites.

15:45.774 --> 15:47.516
See, God wasn't asleep at the wheel.

15:47.556 --> 15:49.518
He hadn't forgotten about his people.

15:49.758 --> 15:51.080
He had always been watching.

15:51.120 --> 15:56.847
He had always been waiting for the right moment, the right circumstances, and the right leader to bring them out of captivity.

15:57.447 --> 16:00.771
Did you catch the verbs that God uses in his conversation with Moses?

16:01.652 --> 16:03.314
God saw their pain.

16:03.906 --> 16:05.628
He heard their cries.

16:05.989 --> 16:10.916
He knew their suffering and he came down to deliver them.

16:11.457 --> 16:13.319
Active, attentive, concerned.

16:13.980 --> 16:20.149
For 400 years, the Israelites thought that God was distant, detached, and disinterested in their pain and their problems.

16:20.429 --> 16:27.980
They had assumed maybe a decent assumption that after they had failed over and over and over again, that at some point God would give up and just move on.

16:28.561 --> 16:32.466
But God says that the entire time he has been paying attention

16:33.154 --> 16:36.699
that now he was ready to get even closer to them.

16:37.820 --> 16:42.267
He wasn't a divine clockmaker that had put all of this together and then walked away.

16:42.908 --> 16:46.753
He wasn't an impersonal force diffused through everything but doing very little.

16:46.773 --> 16:50.218
He wasn't a score keeper, just keeping score in the sky.

16:50.478 --> 16:53.282
He wasn't even just the laws of physics playing themselves out.

16:53.923 --> 16:55.946
Notice the direction of his movement.

16:56.987 --> 16:59.090
I came down.

17:00.098 --> 17:08.911
If you're not familiar with Christianity, or maybe you're only familiar with another religion, basically every religion in the world has the directionality of you going up.

17:09.652 --> 17:18.565
Moral accomplishments, following a specific code of conduct, you are climbing some sort of ladder to get to the God of every other religion.

17:18.826 --> 17:22.111
Here's what sets Christianity the good news of Jesus the gospel apart.

17:22.711 --> 17:24.053
You don't climb up to get him.

17:25.436 --> 17:27.258
It starts by acknowledging you can't.

17:27.979 --> 17:29.842
And the good news is you don't need to.

17:30.306 --> 17:32.529
because he came down.

17:33.250 --> 17:35.052
He comes down to a burning bush.

17:35.733 --> 17:37.936
But this was not just like the spark.

17:37.996 --> 17:41.620
It was this thing that would ultimately culminate in the story that will celebrate at Easter.

17:41.700 --> 17:45.625
It was this future prediction and promise about what God would do for all of us.

17:45.685 --> 17:58.802
And eventually, actually still in our future today, we'll celebrate this again when Jesus comes back again to set things right for the final and permanent restoration of all things.

17:59.522 --> 18:02.225
Now, I'm sure that at this point, Moses was fully on board.

18:02.445 --> 18:12.056
Like, okay, the plan is that you're going to deliver judgment and justice that will free your people that all get to watch from Egyptian captivity.

18:12.096 --> 18:12.717
Let's do it.

18:12.737 --> 18:13.678
Let me get the popcorn.

18:14.799 --> 18:19.004
But God says, oh, no, no, no, Moses, I'm gonna use you to do that.

18:20.225 --> 18:26.132
See, Moses, his response is so close to what I think a lot of us would do, like the way that we would respond in this moment.

18:26.172 --> 18:28.114
The text says this, but Moses said,

18:28.386 --> 18:33.895
to God, who am I that I should go to Pharaoh and bring the children of Israel out of Egypt?"

18:34.596 --> 18:37.240
Now, we might want to be hard on Moses in this moment, but consider this.

18:37.541 --> 18:41.527
What we're hearing him describe is the voice of disqualification.

18:41.588 --> 18:43.451
He's saying, I'm not good enough.

18:44.252 --> 18:46.415
Moses looks at his resume, right?

18:46.435 --> 18:49.220
He sees a significant gap in his work history.

18:50.021 --> 18:53.327
He would have to disclose to any future employer a conviction for murder.

18:53.387 --> 18:55.410
That feels career limiting, right?

18:55.874 --> 19:00.780
He can't have a strong first impression because he has a debilitating stutter and speech impediment.

19:01.381 --> 19:05.426
And at age 80, he qualified for Social Security decades ago.

19:06.907 --> 19:09.631
Moses' question is about identity.

19:10.472 --> 19:17.100
He thinks he can't measure up to the mission, but he's measuring the wrong qualities, the wrong qualifications.

19:17.120 --> 19:19.122
God's response is not a pep talk.

19:19.490 --> 19:24.678
It's not affirming specific, sovereignly appointed qualities that Moses has had and didn't realize.

19:25.038 --> 19:27.823
He actually doesn't argue with Moses' point at all.

19:28.704 --> 19:31.789
Instead, God says, but I will be with you.

19:31.849 --> 19:36.496
In other words, Moses says, who have a high?

19:37.878 --> 19:40.262
And God says, mine.

19:42.305 --> 19:43.186
Do you see the shift?

19:44.194 --> 19:51.702
Moses is wondering how he can do all of this work, and God is reminding him he isn't the one that's going to do all of this work.

19:52.063 --> 19:53.444
God is, and God will be with him.

19:54.505 --> 20:00.191
See, in the desert, we often learn that our qualifications are not what we see primarily in our resume.

20:00.992 --> 20:04.276
They are really, if you're a follower of Jesus, found in the presence of God in your life.

20:05.077 --> 20:06.919
The desert did not disqualify Moses.

20:07.639 --> 20:10.002
It diagnosed his self-sufficiency.

20:10.690 --> 20:14.635
all the areas he had been depending on himself unsuccessfully and unsustainably.

20:15.517 --> 20:20.083
But even with some assurance from God, Moses still had one more question.

20:20.904 --> 20:26.552
Anticipating the conversation that would come when he brought this to the Pharaoh's court, he asks for God's name.

20:26.913 --> 20:28.655
He says, who should I tell them sent me?

20:29.336 --> 20:34.523
And this is a pretty big movement in our passage because the desert, it anchors you in God's name.

20:34.563 --> 20:36.626
And today that may feel insignificant,

20:37.026 --> 20:42.736
But Moses, he's finally realizing that his resume is not the only relevant thing for this assignment.

20:43.417 --> 20:46.823
And when Moses asks for God's name, it's really significant.

20:47.184 --> 20:51.852
See, in the ancient world, knowing a God's name gave you access to that God's power.

20:52.654 --> 20:59.666
It was like being given the contact information for that God that you could reach out whenever you needed and be given access to the power instantly.

21:00.098 --> 21:15.293
Moses is basically saying, if I'm gonna do this crazy life-threatening thing that you ask me to do in a place that I'm wanted for murder and even law abiding people that look like me have been slaves for centuries, I'm gonna go ahead and need some instant and extra support.

21:15.874 --> 21:17.235
I'm gonna need the help line, God.

21:18.136 --> 21:23.181
And if you're unfamiliar with Hebrew literature, God's answer is wild and confusing.

21:23.602 --> 21:27.826
This is what he tells Moses to tell the ruling court in Egypt.

21:28.034 --> 21:37.787
God said to Moses, I am who I am, which, I mean, I just think about that as Moses at the time and I'm like, God, not that helpful, right?

21:37.807 --> 21:42.634
And he said, say this to the people of Israel, I am has sent me to you.

21:43.295 --> 21:51.687
God also said to Moses, say this to the people of Israel, the Lord, the God of your fathers, the God of Abraham, the God of Isaac, the God of Jacob has sent me to you.

21:52.307 --> 21:57.074
This is my name forever and thus I am to be remembered throughout all

21:57.538 --> 21:58.199
generations.

21:58.239 --> 22:02.505
Now, I want to get nerdy with you for just a minute, and some of you are like, get nerdy for a minute.

22:02.565 --> 22:03.626
What's the rest of this been?

22:04.107 --> 22:05.268
And that's hurtful.

22:05.369 --> 22:08.633
I just want you to know that's a hurtful characterization, but I receive it.

22:09.955 --> 22:11.076
But bear with me for just a second.

22:11.096 --> 22:18.226
In English, this idea of I am who I am, it sounds like an ancient version of Popeye introducing himself, if we're honest, right?

22:18.466 --> 22:19.888
I am what I am and that's what I am."

22:19.908 --> 22:23.413
You're like, that's a pretty early reference to a cartoon that you probably don't know.

22:23.633 --> 22:25.916
But in Hebrew, it's kind of incredible.

22:26.056 --> 22:30.903
See, there's a covenant name for God that over time they would grow more and more familiar with.

22:31.003 --> 22:36.330
We pronounce that Yahweh, but actually it was not originally designed with vowels.

22:36.771 --> 22:42.659
It was just these letters that we translate YH or YWH.

22:43.060 --> 22:47.826
It was created that way without vowels so that it would be unpronounceable on purpose

22:47.970 --> 22:50.873
out of reverence, but it meant he is.

22:50.893 --> 22:55.058
It pointed to an eternal self-existence.

22:55.618 --> 23:02.266
That Yahweh pointed to the one who simply is, self-existent, uncaused, uncontained, without end, God.

23:03.047 --> 23:13.138
And so when God says, I am who I am, he is speaking actually from the same root word that gives the covenant name Yahweh, the name that Israel would use to refer to him as he is.

23:13.458 --> 23:15.660
It's like God saying, hey, you know how you talk about he is?

23:15.700 --> 23:17.202
That's me.

23:18.498 --> 23:25.226
God is speaking of himself, and he's revealing his eternal nature to a group of people who thought that hundreds of years was a long time.

23:25.266 --> 23:29.311
But to Yahweh, to the God that was writing to them, it was nothing.

23:30.312 --> 23:31.313
It was like the next day.

23:32.955 --> 23:34.257
See, he isn't going to live forever.

23:34.297 --> 23:35.579
God is not going to live forever.

23:36.960 --> 23:37.881
God is forever.

23:39.403 --> 23:43.168
Pharaoh's reign that seems unshakeable had a timeline.

23:44.309 --> 23:48.434
Israel's suffering that felt like it would have no relief, it had a timeline.

23:48.962 --> 23:53.549
Moses' exile that felt like it was the final word had a timeline.

23:53.870 --> 24:00.520
But Yahweh, still to this day, thousands of years later, still has no timeline.

24:01.542 --> 24:05.488
Moses needed to know that in the desert and you need to know it too, that you worship a God.

24:05.568 --> 24:08.413
A God loves you who has no timeline.

24:09.054 --> 24:13.521
He had let the desert shape who he was and who he believed he could be.

24:13.561 --> 24:16.626
And that's what the desert can do if we're not careful.

24:17.058 --> 24:19.922
See, the desert reminds you what defines you.

24:20.643 --> 24:24.809
It will show you and me the things that we have let seep into our character and calling.

24:25.350 --> 24:29.596
But if you remember nothing else from our time today, remember this, the desert doesn't disqualify you.

24:30.378 --> 24:32.881
It's where God often delivers your destination.

24:33.642 --> 24:35.946
If you want clarity, it never happens in comfort.

24:37.288 --> 24:38.149
It happens in the desert.

24:39.511 --> 24:41.554
God's name means that God

24:41.666 --> 24:48.433
who met Moses in the desert is the same God who is meeting you in your desert, in your life, in your circumstances today.

24:48.473 --> 24:50.014
He hasn't changed.

24:50.375 --> 24:51.275
He hasn't retired.

24:51.576 --> 24:52.557
He hasn't gotten older.

24:52.617 --> 24:54.018
He hasn't lost interest.

24:54.298 --> 24:55.420
He doesn't love you less.

24:55.460 --> 25:07.932
Don't miss this anchor for your soul, this Lent, as we prepare for Easter, as we wait for Easter, both the holiday that we'll celebrate and the remembrance of the hope of the resurrection in the midst of our circumstances and lives.

25:08.272 --> 25:10.034
The desert doesn't disqualify you.

25:10.626 --> 25:17.195
It may be where you finally discover the destination that wasn't about arriving somewhere anyway.

25:18.136 --> 25:25.326
As a matter of fact, it's always been about God appearing with you right now, today, wherever you are and whatever you're going through.

25:25.366 --> 25:26.688
That's the God that gets close.

25:27.629 --> 25:31.254
The burning bush, just like the resurrection, it wasn't an escape hatch for God.

25:31.755 --> 25:34.258
It was an introduction to ordinary people.

25:34.722 --> 25:44.755
to the reality and invitation of a God who loves them and would go to any lengths necessary, even all these thousands of years ago to communicate that hope, it really is for everyone.

25:45.757 --> 25:49.662
See Moses, he needed to know that in the desert and you probably need to know it today too.

25:50.523 --> 25:54.528
Because deserts, they don't just drain your energy, they try to rename you.

25:55.389 --> 25:58.393
The desert is going to try to name you what you're going through.

25:58.433 --> 26:01.938
For some of you, you feel like the desert you're going through is trying to rename you failure.

26:02.594 --> 26:11.343
or delay or divorce or depression or diagnosis or job loss or relapse or infertility or grief or loneliness or burnout.

26:12.884 --> 26:19.311
And if you stay in the desert long enough on your own without God and without people, you start to introduce yourself with your dysfunction.

26:20.792 --> 26:21.633
I'm not feeling anymore.

26:22.534 --> 26:23.435
I'm the one who couldn't.

26:24.216 --> 26:25.417
You're not a daughter anymore.

26:26.218 --> 26:27.159
You're the one who lost.

26:27.179 --> 26:28.340
You're not a husband anymore.

26:29.141 --> 26:30.162
You're the one who blew it.

26:30.306 --> 26:31.367
You're not a believer anymore.

26:31.407 --> 26:32.709
You're the one that God forgot.

26:33.630 --> 26:37.615
And I need you to hear this clearly so that you can hear hopefully what God has for you.

26:37.955 --> 26:42.721
God does not meet Moses in the desert and say, let me see your resume.

26:43.642 --> 26:47.527
He says, take off your sandals.

26:47.547 --> 26:51.812
And then he says a name that outlasts every desert you will ever face.

26:53.755 --> 26:54.015
I am.

26:55.316 --> 26:55.897
Not I was.

26:55.917 --> 26:58.140
Not I will be someday.

26:58.180 --> 26:59.922
I am.

27:01.122 --> 27:05.587
Right here, right now, in this place.

27:06.708 --> 27:10.633
Some of you, you've been waiting to feel close to God again until life gets cleaned up.

27:11.574 --> 27:13.115
Until you feel strong again.

27:13.556 --> 27:14.677
Until you stop crying.

27:14.737 --> 27:15.818
Until you stop doubting.

27:15.858 --> 27:17.100
Until you stop being angry.

27:17.120 --> 27:18.982
Until you stop feeling numb.

27:19.903 --> 27:22.406
But Exodus 3, it tells us the opposite.

27:22.426 --> 27:25.489
It tells us that the desert doesn't disqualify you.

27:25.509 --> 27:27.611
It's where God delivers your real destination.

27:27.872 --> 27:30.034
What He actually wants to do in and through you.

27:30.498 --> 27:32.220
And the destination is not a zip code.

27:32.260 --> 27:33.021
It's not a title.

27:33.061 --> 27:34.322
It's not a relationship status.

27:34.643 --> 27:37.346
It's actually not rooted in your circumstances at all.

27:37.626 --> 27:44.574
The destination has always been that wherever you are, you would say, I know that God is with me.

27:45.615 --> 27:49.700
And I'm going to walk with him, allowing God to name you again.

27:49.740 --> 27:51.582
God meeting you again.

27:51.622 --> 27:54.565
God is steady when you are not.

27:54.686 --> 27:55.266
Thank God.

27:56.187 --> 27:58.610
So here's what I want you to do before we sing in just a minute.

27:59.362 --> 28:08.964
If you're in a desert right now, any kind of desert, a desert that people maybe know about or one that they don't know about, would you just be honest with God in your heart for a moment?

28:09.004 --> 28:11.249
Not out loud, just like for you, with God.

28:11.550 --> 28:13.514
God, here's where I feel exhausted.

28:13.775 --> 28:15.379
Here's where I feel discouraged.

28:15.579 --> 28:18.546
Here's where I feel locked in with no escape.

28:19.554 --> 28:21.076
